<paragraph id="E97036DD3F77FFE0FF76FB45FC5DFB3C" blockId="66.[151,1437,1219,2037]" box="[151,957,1219,1245]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
Size. Maximum known size 2.0 cm total length (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F77FFE0FD56FB45FC51FB3C" author="Schliewen, U. K. &amp; Kovacic, M. &amp; Gerwenka, A. F. &amp; Svensen, R. &amp; Ordines, F." box="[695,945,1219,1245]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="231 - 254" refId="ref64392" refString="Schliewen, U. K., Kovacic, M., Gerwenka, A. F., Svensen, R. &amp; Ordines, F. (2019) Lebetus patzneri (Teleostei: Gobiidae), a new goby species from the Balearic Islands, western Mediterranean, with first records of Lebetus guilleti (Le Danois, 1913) from this area and Norway, and with notes on its biology. Zootaxa, 4706 (2), 231 - 254. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4706.2.2" type="journal article" year="2019">
Schliewen 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F77FFE0FCD4FB45FC86FB3C" box="[821,870,1219,1245]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">et al</emphasis>
. 2019
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F77FFE0FF26FB61FE7BF814" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F77FFE0FF26FB61FA89FA70" blockId="66.[151,1437,1219,2037]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
Morphology. D VI + I,7–9; A I,4-6; P 14-15 (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F77FFE0FD2CFB61FC00FAE0" author="Herler, J. &amp; Kovacic, M." box="[717,992,1255,1281]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="177 - 188" refId="ref56000" refString="Herler, J. &amp; Kovacic, M. (2002) Lebetus guilleti (Teleostei: Gobiidae) in the northern Adriatic Sea: first record and details on the species' morphology. Annales, Series Historia Naturalis, 12, 177 - 188." type="journal article" year="2002">Herler &amp; Kovačić 2002</bibRefCitation>
). Small goby with subcylindrical body, laterally compressed towards caudal fin. Head slightly depressed and fairly long, snout short, eyes large and close together. Caudal peduncle deep, but lower than body depth. First dorsal fin higher than the second dorsal fin; no elongated spines, but breeding males with notably enlarged, sail-like first dorsal fin. Caudal fin rounded. Body covered with scales (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F77FFE0FE60FAF1FD6EFA70" author="Herler, J. &amp; Kovacic, M." box="[385,654,1399,1425]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="177 - 188" refId="ref56000" refString="Herler, J. &amp; Kovacic, M. (2002) Lebetus guilleti (Teleostei: Gobiidae) in the northern Adriatic Sea: first record and details on the species' morphology. Annales, Series Historia Naturalis, 12, 177 - 188." type="journal article" year="2002">Herler &amp; Kovačić 2002</bibRefCitation>
), which are poorly visible on live specimen photographs (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F77FFE0FAF6FAF1FABBFA70" box="[1303,1371,1399,1425]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1982,2006]" captionTargetBox="[158,1430,1111,1959]" captionTargetId="figure-41@16.[158,1430,1111,1959]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 8. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Lebetus guilleti. Photo by J. Herler, Selce, Croatia, Northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601587" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601587/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F77FFE0FF26FA1DFE7BF8FC" blockId="66.[151,1437,1219,2037]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
Live coloration. Head and most predorsal area grayish in males, brownish in females. Body with a pattern of alternating dark and pale, slightly oblique broad bars. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F77FFE0FD14FA38FBC5FA1D" bold="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">A white area below the first dorsal fin, followed by a well obliquely-delineated dark area between bases of second dorsal and anal fins</emphasis>
(which contains an oblong white spot ventrally), 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F77FFE0FEACF980FC68F9C0" bold="true" box="[333,904,1542,1569]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">contrasting with a plain white caudal peduncle</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F77FFE0FC7AF981FC01F9C0" box="[923,993,1543,1569]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1982,2006]" captionTargetBox="[158,1430,1111,1959]" captionTargetId="figure-41@16.[158,1430,1111,1959]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 8. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Lebetus guilleti. Photo by J. Herler, Selce, Croatia, Northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601587" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601587/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Rear caudal peduncle and caudal-fin base dark brown. White body area extending onto most of pectoral fin. Additional narrow rusty red bars can be present over pale and dark areas below dorsal fins. Males’ enlarged first dorsal fin grayish to white with 2-3, often faint, oblique yellow to orange bands, second dorsal fin with black margin, 4 oblique yellow to orange bands and sometimes a large blue-edged black blotch on its anterior corner. Females’ triangular first dorsal fin white to graybrown with a small green round spot between fifth and sixth spines, second dorsal fin somewhat transparent, both dorsal fins with visible or indistinct oblique orange bands (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F77FFE0FCA5F959FBBAF918" author="Herler, J. &amp; Kovacic, M." box="[836,1114,1759,1785]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="177 - 188" refId="ref56000" refString="Herler, J. &amp; Kovacic, M. (2002) Lebetus guilleti (Teleostei: Gobiidae) in the northern Adriatic Sea: first record and details on the species' morphology. Annales, Series Historia Naturalis, 12, 177 - 188." type="journal article" year="2002">Herler &amp; Kovačić 2002</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F77FFE0FB89F959FA78F918" author="Hope, R. &amp; Shucksmith, R." box="[1128,1432,1759,1785]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="98" refId="ref56425" refString="Hope, R. &amp; Shucksmith, R. (2010) Most northerly record of Europe's smallest marine fish Guillet's goby Lebetus guilleti in the Shetland Islands, Scotland. Marine Biodiversity Records, 3, e 98. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 175526721000103 X" type="journal article" year="2010">Hope &amp; Shucksmith 2010</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F77FFE0FF76F885FE6FF8FC" author="Schliewen, U. K. &amp; Kovacic, M. &amp; Gerwenka, A. F. &amp; Svensen, R. &amp; Ordines, F." box="[151,399,1795,1821]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="231 - 254" refId="ref64392" refString="Schliewen, U. K., Kovacic, M., Gerwenka, A. F., Svensen, R. &amp; Ordines, F. (2019) Lebetus patzneri (Teleostei: Gobiidae), a new goby species from the Balearic Islands, western Mediterranean, with first records of Lebetus guilleti (Le Danois, 1913) from this area and Norway, and with notes on its biology. Zootaxa, 4706 (2), 231 - 254. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4706.2.2" type="journal article" year="2019">
Schliewen 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F77FFE0FEF2F885FEA4F8FC" box="[275,324,1795,1821]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">et al</emphasis>
. 2019
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F77FFE0FF26F8A1FCB6F8A0" blockId="66.[151,1437,1219,2037]" box="[199,854,1831,1857]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F77FFE0FE9EF8A1FDDAF8A1" authorityName="Schliewen, Kovacic &amp; Ordines" authorityYear="2019" box="[383,570,1831,1857]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Lebetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="patzneri">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F77FFE0FE9EF8A1FDDAF8A1" box="[383,570,1831,1857]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Lebetus patzneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
